==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hawe</ets>,
AS. <ets>haga</ets>; akin to D. <ets>haag</ets> headge, G.
<ets>hag</ets>, <ets>hecke</ets>, Icel. <ets>hagi</ets> pasture, Sw.
<ets>hage</ets>, Dan. <ets>have</ets> garden. ⟦root⟧12. Cf.
<er>Haggard</er>, <er>Ha-ha</er>, <er>Haugh</er>,
<er>Hedge</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A hedge; an inclosed garden or yard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And eke there was a polecat in his <qex>haw</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fruit of the hawthorn.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The third eyelid, or nictitating membrane. See
<cref>Nictitating membrane</cref>, under <er>Nictitate</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <ets>ha</ets> an interjection of
wonder, surprise, or hesitation.]</ety> <def>An intermission or
hesitation of speech, with a sound somewhat like <xex>haw!</xex> also,
the sound so made.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Hums or <xex>haws</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Congreve.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To stop, in speaking, with a sound
like <xex>haw</xex>; to speak with interruption and
hesitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cut it short; don't prose -- don't hum and <qex>haw</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chesterfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>hemming and hawing</b></col> <cd>speaking hesitantly and
inarticulately, with numerous pauses and interjections.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hawed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦add⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hawing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also
<ets>hoi</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[Perhaps connected with <ets>here</ets>,
<ets>hither</ets>; cf., however, F. <ets>huhau</ets>, <ets>hurhau</ets>,
<ets>hue</ets>, interj. used in turning a horse to the right, G.
<ets>hott</ets>, <ets>h⟦uum⟧</ets>, interj. used in calling to a
horse.]</ety> <def>To turn to the near side, or toward the driver; --
said of cattle or a team: a word used by teamsters in guiding their
teams, and most frequently in the imperative. See
<er>Gee</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To haw and gee</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To
haw and gee about</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to go from one thing to another
without good reason; to have no settled purpose; to be irresolute or
unstable.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haw</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Haw
<hw>Haw</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to turn, as a team, to the
near side, or toward the driver; <as>as, to <ex>haw</ex> a team of
oxen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To haw and gee</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To
haw and gee about</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to lead this way and that at
will; to lead by the nose; to master or control.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hawaiian</ent>⟦br⟧
